description.text: This print was born out of a need to organize recharchable batteries for use with photography flashes such as the Canon 580 or 430.  It holds 4 AA batteries and indicates whether they are charged or used based on how the two halves are oriented.  One piece has a full battery icon on one side and an empty battery icon on the other.  The other piece has an arrow icon that points to whichever battery icon indicates the current charge.  The two halves can be held together by a rubber band fitted around the grooves, if the fit is not snug enough to hold them together.

There are two parts to print.  My version was printed on a Cupcake with a Mk6 extruder.  The interior walls are thin, so may have threads or may even be partial.  I also sized them larger than the diameter of most batteries to account for shrinkage.  However, when printed, the fit was nice and snug, and a little clean-up with a hobby knife was all that was needed.  
Sketch-up files included for your modding pleasure.

description.text:
Study whole.stl before printing.

You need one of pin0 and 12 of pin.

Make sure to split the bunched-up parts while plating these. (use your slicer or "Split to shells" in Meshmixer)

Note that it might take some heating and bending at the base of the pins to get all the pins pointing straight up. I had to make the holes a bit loose (now requires glue), so I can get pins in and out if they cause a ring to hang and need adjustment/cleaning. So make sure it's 90 degrees before you glue, and of course, glue with the pins inside top.stl. I do it pair by pair.

The original is a great idea but I consider it unprintable, mostly in terms of fragile structures, too much cleaning, and too much material. Also it only spins one way.

https://youtu.be/9Y8ZmZ1SVv0

(Huh, I guess the whole thing was copied from here perhaps? http://youtu.be/ZqzjAmPFND8 )

(And if you're thinking "dice!", no, sadly it's not very good for dice. I made a static border that snaps on to the top and keeps 3 dice from falling off, but still, the motion is too linear, the dice barely ever turn on a second axis. But I like the way you think!)

If you print it and love it, please do upload a Make and consider tipping! :)
Also please check my profile for my Etsy, Pinshape etc...

comments.text:
Hi, Give the plate a good clean with acetone and the a couple of coats of hairspray.
Print until you start having problem and then just apply another coat of hairspray. After a while you will get a buildup of hairspray and need to clean the plate completely with hot soapy water.Once dry repeat the process.
If you have a particularly troublesome ABS print that keeps lifting applying a coat of ABS juice to the cold plate, on top of the hairspray. Be sure to let the glass plate cool down before removing as it's much easier.
There are no set rules, experiment to find what works best with your workflow.

title: G2S Universal Effector Lazer Zprobe
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I said I wasn't planning to design a Z-probe, but inspiration struck and this is the result. This "probe" uses a laser diode beam, projected at a shallow angle, to measure a fixed height, approximately 30mm below the surface to which it is mounted. The laser spot moves horizontally approximately 9mm for each millimeter of vertical movement. A trigger condition (HIGH) is signaled when the light sensor "sees" the laser spot come into its view.

There is an enable input which may be driven directly from an Arduino output pin to activate (HIGH) or deactivate (LOW) the laser. For manual control, you may either switch the Enable line to ground to turn the laser off, or simply switch the 5 volt power supplied to the circuit.

Because this is an optical device, it can be affected by the type of surface material being measured. It works great on blue tape or glass with glue stick applied. I assume aluminum with glue stick should also work well but I am unable to test that. Performance on clean aluminum, BuildTak, etc. is unknown at this time. Clean glass does not work well, and addition of hair spray does not help significantly. Be careful to remove any loose debris from the bed before probing, as these could cause false triggering.

CAUTION: Laser light can be hazardous to your eyes. Even these relatively low power diodes are capable of causing headaches and temporary blind spots.

You will need some additional components and soldering skills to assemble this device. Here is a list of components I used:

  • ATtiny85 micro controller
  • 8-pin dual in-line chip socket
  • 6mm laser diode
  • Light sensitive resister
  • 3mm green LED (trigger indicator)
  • 1K resistor
  • 220 resistor
  • 39K resistor

Since the ATtiny85 is a bare chip (rather than an Arduino board), you will need an In-System-Programmer (ISP) to write the LazerRanger.ino sketch into it. These programmers are inexpensive and readily available from many vendors. You can also configure almost any Arduino board for use as an ISP, as shown here and here. You will need to load some support data into your Arduino IDE, which makes ATtiny devices appear in the "Boards" list. This is also covered in the ISP tutorials above. Be sure to select the "ATtiny85, 8MHz Internal clock" and burn the bootloader to configure the chip for higher speed operation.

title: Kossel Layer Fan Duct and Mount E3D

description.text:
Layer / part fan mount and duct for your Ultibots K250 BSE (and likely other derivatives).

I couldnt find a fan duct and mount solution that worked for me. Common issues were: restricted XY travel limits, poor performance, or just plain flimsy. Whats an engineer do in that situation? He designs his own. Mine is by no means perfect. I know there are issues with the angles but if printed in PC it wont get soft and will stay rigid.

Designed for a standard 5015 centrifugal fan to mount to the Ultibots mag ball efector. I recommend printing in polycarbonate for the temperature resistance. If you print in something else put some kapton between heater block and duct for insulation.

I uploaded the native Creo .prt so feel free to modify to your needs. I also included a STEP and STL. Walls on the duct (k250_annularfan & k250_annularfan_cs1.stl) are 0.5mm thick, print with a 0.5mm nozzle. I suggest keeping those equal to ensure you get a good single wall so modify CAD to your nozzle size or get a 0.5mm nozzle. I do not plan to make any updates at this time.

07/04/16 UPDATE: Found issue with "5015_franbracket_final.stl", deleted old one and uploaded new unbroken faceted model.

description.text:
Here’s my photolog of how I solved a sunroof-meets-Thule problem with 3D printing and mold making. My wife’s Mazda 5 has a Thule roof rack mounted on factory hard points. When she tries to open her sunroof, the window hit the rack bar. So, I created a part using the 3D printer she got me to raise the rack up .5 inches. This probably the most useful thing I’ve created with a 3D printer to date. You can see in the photos how the window hits the bar, how I made the silicone mold, and then cast the parts.

The boots for the roof rack are Thule Fit Kit KIT3080.
https://www.thule.com/en-us/us/support/spare-parts?p=3080999&sc={8E447224-06C8-4AB8-B07B-A5367BB55EB8}

Notes:

With the Mini, you can get great prints if you pre-heat the build plate with a heat gun (or blow dryer). Use an infrared thermometer to measure the temperature. I found that if I heated it to about 60 deg C, at the time the print head started, then I got good part adhesion without much warping. A little warping is okay in this part because the final part will mold to the Thule rack (if cast using urethane).

Here are the test parts. The one on the left is the actual size I needed: 0.5 inches tall. The other two are for making the mold. I made the mold versions taller so I could make different heights of parts if needed, just by filling the mold with more resin.

Here's the problem: The sunroof on this Mazda 5 hits the Thule rack using the factory hard-points. This prevents the window from opening all the way (this image is as far as it goes). When the window hits the rack's crossbar, the motor stalls (which can't be good for the motor). Another view of the window hitting the Thule cross bar. Deconstructing the rack. Note the steel, with only one bolt, holding the system together. Here's the bare factory hard-point, with the bolt sticking up. I didn't remove the bolts. Test fit of the PLA part in the Thule rack foot boot. Tall part, ready for the silicone mold pour. The mold box was 3x3x6 The PLA printed parts were made into a mold using Smooth-on OOMOO 30 silicone casting liquid. Detail was pretty good for the part. Note the undercuts. This photo was taken after I'd cast 4 parts and the mold started to degrade a little: note the chunk missing from the lower-right undercut. Release agent: silicone lubricant ( I added 4 registration marks so I could easily tell how thick the part was, as I was pouring resin into the mold. Cast parts, using Smooth-on ONYX Slow casting resin. It has a Shore D hardness of 80 if heat cured at 250 deg F for 4 hours (I didn't do this, yet). Note that the resin climbed the sides of the silicone mold, so I used a metal file to flatten the edges after demolding. Here's the final cast part being test-fit. Putting the rack back together, with the .5 Note that the bolt was long enough to completely engage the nut, despite being the original Thule part. Fully installed. You can see the rise clearly here. Victory! The window opens! Fully open position, with the rack up 0.5

title: Ultimaker Hot End Thermal Isolation Sock Mold

description.text:
A multipart mold that lets you cast a high-temperature silicone thermal isolation "sock" that fits over the standard ultimaker hot end. Because silicone is much less conductive that metal, the sock will considerably reduce heat transfer from the hot end to the cooling airflow, resulting in lower cooling air temperature and thus better cooling -- cooling air downstream of the hot end is approximately 10F cooler when using the sock.  
V11 of this object exposes the top part of the filament tube so that there is a stronger temperature gradient, and less chance for clogging. Note that the photos are from the previous version.

NOTE: These instructions have changed since the previous version! Print the 4 parts of the mold (you can omit the top cap if you want, it is a legacy of the previous design and not really needed anymore). You will only need support on the insert part -- print it with the hexagonal feature UP. Note: you should use these instructions to test-assemble your mold before actually using them to make a cast. Tap the holes in the insert to accept a #6 bolt (or close metric equivalent. Tap the top holes first, then tap the single bottom hole as deeply as you can. Tap the vertical holes in the side parts of the mold #6 as well. Coat the inside surfaces of the side parts with a thin layer of vaseline. Assemble the side parts using 8 short #6 bolts and nuts, being careful to get the seams aligned. Breathe on the inside surfaces for 30 seconds to humidify them; this will help the silicone to set faster. Apply a thin coat of vaseline to the insert and to the top cap (if you decide to use it; you can just use a straight-edge to flatten the top of the silicone if you prefer), and do the heavy breathing routine on them as well. Assemble them with two short bolts. Fill the mold about 80% full of silicone, stirring it as you do to ensure there are no air pockets. Make sure the small indents in the side walls are completely full of silicone; these strengthen the final cast part). You can stir a small amount of cornstarch if you like to speed up the curing. Different silicones have different temperature tolerances, elasticity and ease of release. My experience is that Permatex Ultra Copper works best. Gently push the insert into the mold, but not all the way. It will be a tight fit, and you need to keep it properly aligned. Silicone will start to smush up. Push a long bolt through the hole in the bottom of the mold, through the silicone, and into the threaded hole in the bottom of the insert. Partially tighten this bolt. If you are using the top cap, insert 2 bolts through the top cap into the threaded holes in the side parts and partially tighten them. Now gently start tightening the bolts. If using the top cap, your goal is to get the bottom bolt tightened completely while you still have a few mm to go on the top. As you tighten, silicone should flow up and out of the gap beween the top cap and the side parts. If you are not using the top cap, then when the insert is fully tightened down, just use a straight-edge to scrape off excess silicone; the insert will be level with the top of the mold halves. Tip: you may find this Toothpaste Key useful in dispensing the silicone. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:35064 Now you must wait for the silicone to cure. As the mold is a thick one, this can take some time. If at any time during the following process you find that any exposed part of the mold has not cured, just add a little extra fresh silicone, smooth down the surface, breathe on it, and put the mold back together. I recommend the following sequence: After 12 hours, remove all the bolts except the bottom one. Use a box cutter to slice around the perimeter of the top cap (if you are using it) and remove it, exposing the top of the mold. Put the entire thing under a tap for a few seconds to increase the humidity. After 24 hours, remove the bottom bolt. After 48 hours, everything should be fully cured. Gently lever apart the side parts by inserting a wedge (like a small flathead screwdriver) between the wings that have the bolt holes. Take your time, and proceed by applying progressively more pressure and waiting for the adhesion to naturally break. You can easily trim any flash that occurs on the mold seams or on the top of the mold using nail scissors. Removing the insert is the most delicate part of the job. Use a small blunt probe (like a fork tine) to gently break the adhesion around the perimeter, gradually going deeper. The silicone is very stretchy, but if you push it too hard, you can tear it. You will soon get to the point where you can insert a finger tip between the silicone and the square part of the insert. Gently increase the pressure and slowly the adhesion will break and you will be able to rotate the insert out of the casting. Soak the silicone casting overnight in a cup of soapy water, then run it through a dishwasher to remove any residual vaseline. If you don't do this, the vaseline will burn when it comes in contact with the hot end. To install, arrange the sensor and heater element wires on the hot end so they are as vertical as possible, then slip the sock on from front to back. With a little wiggling, it'll slip right into place, with the bump at the front hooking over the front edge of the hot end block.

Headphone holder for attaching to a desk or shelf. It's a variation on my original design:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1644192
but with a screw in clamp that allows you to adjust to a shelf with a max depth of 45mm.

15 Dec 2016 - added a version with a shorter stem to suit smaller printers and headphones with a narrower head band. Inspired by @xenomorphdelombre remix. Also sports additional 3.5mm and 7mm holes for male headphone plugs on the neck given that the original holes would be covered by your headphones in this version.

11 Jan 2017 - Added a stl with a 20mm shorter stem so there's not so much wastage with thicker desks.

11 Jan 2017 - Added a version with a 30mm extension to the depth of the clamp section to better support desks with a large beveled edge. NOTE - experimental, I haven't personally printed this one yet.

description.text:
J'ai conçu un support vertical pour les bobines géantes (10kg de filament ! ) de chez Optimus.
Pourquoi un support vertical? Parce qu'il existait un phénomène de balourd avec les grosses bobines. Il était difficile de trouver un équilibre, il arrivait que la bobine reparte dans le sens inverse de son déroulement. Le poids important générait une tension sur le fil suffisante pour désamorcer l'imprimante.
Avec ce support vertical, ce phénomène de balourd disparait totalement. Par ailleurs, l'unique roulement à billes est largement suffisant pour faire tourner facilement l'énorme bobine.
Notez que ce support est compatible avec n'importe quelle bobine, il suffit d'imprimer des oreilles standards.

description.text: Ripped straight from the game,no cleaning has been done.
A small sleeve that keeps dishes from wearing away the soft coating on a dishwasher rack.

Over the years, our dishes have worn away the soft plastic coating on the dishwasher rack. The underlying steel has rusted and leaves stains on the dish rims. This shall not be tolerated! These doodads slip over the upright pins and rest on the horizontal rods, secured with a blob of acrylic or silicone adhesive. The dishes now snuggle into the protector and no longer touch the rack: problem solved. The horizontal half-cylinder requires interior support to prevent sagging. The ridged support structure (colored cyan in the models) should come out fairly easily; I used a concave-end nail set punch and a brass hammer. You must tweak the OpenSCAD source code to match your dishwasher's rods and Skeinforge / Slic3r extrusion parameters; the holes in the STL model probably don't have the right sizes. Multiply the STL model to print an array of parts that will give each protector time to cool before the next layer... and because you'll need a bunch. You can fit 18 copies on a Thing-O-Matic platform without crowding. More details and backstory on my blog at
http://softsolder.com/2012/01/16/dishwasher-rack-protectors/

description.text:
This idea came to me not too long ago. These disks on a motor will spin, and through one of the holes you can put your beam (laser, photons, etc pretty much any beam or whatever so long as the beam doesn't penetrate the plastic xD). So as the disk is spinning, its chopping your beam and giving you a frequency. Also, if you use aluminum foil to cover the plastic and not the holes you can prob play with other radiations lol. I think you can also use these disks as little "observing windows" that provide a flash frame of signal.

Calculations are as follows:

Frequency Created = revolutions per minute*holes in the disk.

so if you're doing 200 spins per second and you're using the 24hole disk, you'll have a frequency of 4800Hz. Or 4800 flash frames. Lol.

I also included the original template of the disk, so you can open it up on sketchup or whatever and use push/pull function to make your own patterns for your research!! I'll see if I can make a stand, or a setup to show how it works.... or maybe someone else can!!! I'd like to see someone make this on a much smaller scale with a tiny hole and thousands of apertures on a disk so the max attainable frequency is huge!!!

NOTE: The disks are a little thin. Just use push/pull function to thicken them up.

description.text:
This is a revision of RotoScan's Space Shuttle model, with most of the major components fixed to be properly manifold and normals corrected (according to both Blender and Slic3r) where needed. I also took the time to un-triangulate much of the models' faces for the sake of easier editing later, if necessary.

I kept everything as close to RotoScan's dimensions and shapes as possible (which is to say, no more than a few hundredths of a millimeter difference). It's not a re-draw, rather it consisted mostly of deleting faces and dissolving-out edges and vertexes and re-creating them a little at a time (so that I always have multiple original vertexes to model against).

The "mid" section of the Orbiter is unchanged from RotoScan's original.

Also, I've included the Blender work files I created during the revision, and a plated .amf.xml of the Orbiter and its Boosters since they're all printed in the same color anyway.

Update: 09/05/2016: I added another Anchor point on the bottom of the bracket to give it a nice complete seal on the wall. Depending on how its screwed in and if the wall is flush, the bottom with start pulling up as seen in one of the original pictures.

This is a Microsoft Surface Pro 3 Wall mount. I designed this cause all the other designs I saw on Thingiverse did not allow me to keep my surface inside its case. The case is a UAG Surface pro 3 Case with a Microsoft keyboard cover attached. Nothing needs to be removed when placed in the dock as you can see from the pictures. The only thing is if you have this exact same case you will need to extend the charging port opening if you wish to use the dock station Microsoft provides as an accessory. The Case does not give enough clearance to the dock but since its rubber, i just used an exact-o knife and cut away to get the right size. If not then just use the regular charger and turn it upside down. It will still charge.

Special Note

Use drywall anchors as to prevent the weight from making the surface fall.

Measurments

This was measured witha caliper from the highest point on the corners of the case.

description.text:
A kinematic mount (KM) is an opto-mechanical component used to adjust precisely the tip and tilt of a mirror (or lens), while it holds the component securely in place. The design presented here, is based on the work of Doug Marret that can be found on http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1004337.

The mount is implemented by printing two pieces of plastic (files KinematicMount_top and KinematicMount_bottom) that are joint together using a sphere and two springs secured with two rods on each side. The drive screw mechanism is built using two nuts that are embedded into the plastic. Two M4 screws with rounded nuts in one end are used to adjust the tip and tilt respectively. The rounded nuts are used to keep the two plastic pieces into position and to reduce any unwanted motion. For additional information go to http://arxiv.org/pdf/1606.09563.pdf

List of materials
1 Steel sphere 8 mm diameter
4 Hex nut M4
2 Rounded nut M4
2 Screw M4, 4cm long
2 Tension spring, 1 cm long
4 Metal rods, 1 cm long

A translation stage (TS) is a component typically used to vary the position of an object along a single axis. The resolution of the moving platform is determined by the drive screw mechanism used to move the platform.

The translation stage is composed of the two pieces shown in the figures (TranslatioinStage_up and TranslationStage_bottom). Unlike a traditional system, the stage printed has two rods fixed to the moving section and the walls of the main platform act as bearings. With this scheme, it was possible to obtain a very stable and robust linear motion along the axis of the rods. The drive screw mechanism is built using a single nut that is embedded in one wall of the main platform. An M4 screw with a rounded nut at one end is used to set the position of the moving section over a range of 1.0 cm. For additional information go to http://arxiv.org/pdf/1606.09563.pdf

An integrating sphere is an optical component composed of a hollow spherical cavity that has two small windows orientated at 90◦ one with respect to the other. The first window corresponds to the input port whereas the other is the output port where a detector is located. For commercial devices, the interior of the sphere is covered with a diffuse reflective coating. When light enters to the sphere, it is reflected equally in all directions due to scattering. As a result, an integrating sphere is a device that can be used to measure optical power, while the spatial information of the input beam is destroyed (i.e. beam shape and entrance angle).

In the figures is shown the 3D printed integrating sphere developed. The hollow sphere is printed using white PLA. In our design the output window allows to use any of the following detectors: webcam or Raspberry Pi camera.

A program written in Python is used to calibrate the integrating sphere with respect to a known reference and also to perform further power measurements. For additional information go to http://arxiv.org/pdf/1606.09563.pdf
